'''Gambling Hangover''' was the theme of an [[Australia]]n [[social marketing]] campaign to help young male [[gambler]]s.
==The campaign== The two-year campaign was created by [[Sydney]] agency The Campaign Palace on behalf of the [[Responsible Gambling Fund]], a part of the [[New South Wales Office of Liquor, Gaming and Racing]].
It targeted men aged 18–25 in the "morning after" phase following a gambling binge, when they were most likely to seek help for [[problem gambling]].<ref>{{cite news | last =Apap | first =Veronica | coauthors = | title =Campaign to curb Illawarra gambling | work =[[Illawarra Mercury]] | pages = | language = | publisher = | date =2008-04-07 | url =http://www.illawarramercury.com.au/news/local/news/general/campaign-to-curb-illawarra-gambling/803596.aspx?storypage=2 | accessdate = 2009-04-06}}</ref> It identified the three main symptoms of a gambling hangover as "a sick feeling," "anxiety and regrets," and "not liking yourself."<ref>{{cite news | last =Masters | first =Clare | coauthors = | title =New gambling hangover campaign targets problem gamblers | work =[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)]] | pages = | language = | publisher = | date =2008-05-03 | url =http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,23687108-5001021,00.html | accessdate = 2009-04-06}}</ref>
Ads were placed where young men were likely to see them in the morning: in train stations, on buses, on morning radio, and in morning newspapers. Young men were urged to visit gamblinghangover.nsw.gov.au, to [[SMS]] for more information, or to call a [[telephone counseling|helpline]] number if they recognised the gambling hangover symptoms in themselves.
Responses to the helpline and in follow-up research showed the phrase had moved into common usage among young men, and 50 percent of those surveyed were able to recall the campaign.{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}
